Macedonians vote in referendum on whether to change the name of the country
The Macedonian people voted in a referendum on Sunday on whether to change their country's name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", which would resolve a long-standing dispute with Greece that has blocked its bids to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which includes the province of Macedonia, claims that the name of its northern neighbor represents a claim to its territory, and has vetoed its accession to NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments signed an agreement based on the proposal of a new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority of Macedonia's population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum, and the boycott campaign cast doubt on whether the voter turnout would meet the minimum of 50 percent needed to hold the referendum.
The question put to the referendum was as follows: “Do you support membership in NATO and the EU, subject to the agreement with Greece?”
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged after the breakup of Yugoslavia, should pay this price for joining organizations such as the EU and NATO.
“I came today to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that it can live freely under the auspices of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us,” says 79-year-old Olivera Georgievskaya, a resident of Skopje.
A sufficient number of members of parliament said they would follow the outcome of the vote to make it decisive, although it has no binding legal force.
Changing the name will require a two-thirds majority of the members of parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that there were no reports of violations by 13:00.
However, turnout was only 16 percent, compared with 34 percent in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters voted.
“I have come to vote for my children, our place in Europe,” says 62-year-old Yose Tanevski, a voter from the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Du<0xC5><0xA1>ko voted in favour of a referendum in Macedonia on changing the country’s name, which will pave the way for its accession to NATO and the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the parliament building in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small stage, placing chairs in front of the tents installed by those citizens who are going to boycott the referendum.
“We are in favor of membership in NATO and the EU, but we want to unite with a high head, and not beating the thresholds of bureaucratic cabinets,” Kavadarkov said.
“Yes, we are citizens of a poor country, but we also have a sense of our own dignity.
If they don’t want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to other countries like China and Russia and become part of Euro-Asian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says that NATO membership will bring investments in Macedonia, which is so necessary for this country, where the unemployment rate is more than 20 percent.
“I believe that the vast majority will be in favour, because more than 80 percent of our citizens support the EU and NATO,” Zaev said after the vote.
He believes that a positive response will be the “guarantee of our prosperous future.”
A poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Political Studies found that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would take part in the referendum, but that’s below the required turnout.
In another survey conducted by Macedonian TV channel Telecom-TV, it turned out that 57 percent of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of them said they would vote positively.
For a referendum to take place, the turnout must be 50 percent plus one vote.
The referendum would be the first serious blow to pro-Western government policies since it came to power in May last year.
