Independent schools in Scotland continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was once again confirmed in 2018: outstanding exam results demonstrated individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other socially significant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), with more than 30,000 students across Scotland, seeking to provide the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further higher education, their chosen career, as well as for the status of world citizens.
As part of the educational sector that is responsible for the development and implementation of an individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a person in a language that he understands, you are calling to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, then you speak to his heart.”
This is a convincing proof that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships with citizens of other countries and be able to trust them.
According to the results of the last exams this year, we see that the languages occupy a leading position in the league tables and have the highest score on the results of examinations in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of students who studied foreign languages received the highest grade “A”.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 per cent of students received an "A" in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of German learners, 69 per cent of French learners and 63 per cent of Spanish learners also received an "A".
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
At present, language subjects are in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that among the reasons that made it difficult for employers to fill vacant jobs, 17 percent had a lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are needed in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the student chooses, if he learns a second language, in the future he will get a real advantage by mastering another additional skill that will be useful to him during his later life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adult Britons in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to support the conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit percentage — it is spoken by 15 percent of respondents.
That’s why investing in language education is so important right now.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of developing countries, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
There is a wide variety of languages taught in schools in Scotland – each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in light of the country’s future development by 2020 – such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of your child, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with teaching staff, whose members are specialists in these languages.
Independent schools in Scotland aim to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, no matter what future awaits them.
At present, it cannot be denied that, in the global business environment, languages continue to be vital to the country ' s future development, and this should be reflected in education accordingly.
In fact, modern languages really need to be seen as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits for Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edwards, Director of the Council of Independent Schools of Scotland
