While Ri reiterated North Korea’s already-sounding grievances against Washington’s “phased” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for step-by-step steps, his statement seemed important in the sense that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization without control, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the incumbent U.S. president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12; then Kim promised to start moving towards “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” and Trump promised North Korea security guarantees.
North Korea seeks to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists that ‘denuclearization must be done first,’ and raises the level of pressure through sanctions to enforce its goal, and even objects to the ‘declaration of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
