Harvard students learn to relax in special courses
The new course, introduced this year at Harvard University, has helped all entry-level students learn to sleep more and fight the chauvinist culture of uninterrupted caffeine consumption with the goal of waking up “overnight.”
One of the academics found that the most successful students in the world often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery, he lit up with the idea of introducing such a course, having previously presented a report on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning processes.
“At the end of my talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘It’s a pity I only found out about this now that I’m almost finishing my studies.’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, talks about how a healthy sleep habit contributes to academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves a person’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Health Service, says the university has decided to introduce this course after it was found that students experience a severe lack of sleep during the school week.
The class lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
One section of the class offers an image of a dorm room where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, simulators, and books, get information about how each of these actions and substances — coffee, light, which causes lack of sleep — affect sports performance, and how important it is to get enough sleep every day.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The interactive campus map encourages course participants to reflect on their daily lives.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behavior of students at once.
But we believe that they have a right to know, like any other person has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects their health,” Chaisler added.
According to him, the false sense of pride that a person can “smell all night” is still quite common, and modern technologies, as well as increasing pressure on students, mean that sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
A sufficient amount of good quality sleep is the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even to combat excess weight, he said, as lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, making it constantly feel hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaisler develop the course by attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread this information throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar study program before entering a competitive institution.
