The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet for Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that claims to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on the open platform Berners-Lee Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people to give access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt’s goal was to gain “world domination.”
“We have to do it now,” he says of his startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid technology, which allows people to create their own “personal online data storage” or POD.
It can contain contact lists, cases, as well as a calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools for working with data.
The application works on the same principle as Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify - everything can be used in one browser at the same time.
The uniqueness of the personal online data storage is that it is fully managed by the user, who can access any necessary information.
The company calls this principle “personal empowerment through data.”
According to company CEO John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company has provided the resources, processes and related skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several full-time developers contracted to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to build their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not in talks with Facebook and Google about whether his company should make drastic changes that will change all of their business models overnight.
“We don’t ask for permission.”
Berners-Lee wrote in a Medium post published on Saturday that “Inrupt’s mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee’s voice has been quite influential in the debate on net neutrality.
Even by launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Internet Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this next era of the Internet,” says Berners-Lee.
