The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
A new study, conducted at a Scottish Highlands estate, aims to show how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is to be hoped that the data obtained will allow a new look at the behavior of unique winged mammals and will help in the further conservation of the species.
The study, organized by scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland, will study common bats, soprano bats, as well as brown long-haired bats and Dobanton nocturnals inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special registrars will be installed at some points around the site to monitor the activity of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of screams, as well as the activities for which different groups of these animals are responsible.
Then a habitat map will be drawn up and a report prepared to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation adviser, hopes these results will show which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help identify the main areas of habitat management work, such as the formation of meadows, as well as ways to maintain forest areas in a state optimal for bats and other related species.
Populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are at risk of extinction due to construction and development works that affect their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can pose hazards, as well as duct tape for flies, chemical treatment of building materials and hunting domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their night hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to pinpoint obstacles on the flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land nationwide, takes bat populations very seriously.
The organization employs ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, field inspections, and sometimes rescue work.
The organization even set up Scotland’s first and only bat reservation at the Threate estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten species of Scottish bats.
Real estate manager David Thompson says the property is the perfect area for them.
“Here at Threate, a great place for bats,” he says.
“There are old buildings here, lots of old trees and all the elements of a good habitat.
But much about bats remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need for a successful existence.”
It recalls the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance within private possessions, since unintentionally destroying one nest can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young individuals, and possibly even the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected by law, their destruction, harassment or destruction of their habitats is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish bat conservation officer, calls on the public to help.
She says, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know how their many separate species live.”
